Former Presidential aspirant in 2019 and executive director of Nigerian-American Council (NAC), Dr. Okey Samuel Mbonu, has urged the Federal Government to ensure national security of its citizens saying the images of horrific murders by Nigerian terrorists are now at the center of the world attention”. Mbonu said this on Tuesday during his meeting with the new US Ambassador to Nigeria, Mary Beth Leonard, at the Washington DC think-tank, “Center for Security and International Studies (CSIS)”, where he discussed matters of rising international concern on Nigeria, especially on security and other important matters. According to him, he said, “Where the government fails to live up to its primary responsibility, of ensuring the safety and security of citizens, they may leave citizens with no option but to revert to the basic human doctrine of self-defense.” Speaking on the future of Nigeria’s politics, Mbonu noted that, “equity and convention dictates the next President of Nigeria in 2023 and it would be from the Southeast region of Nigeria.” Mbonu said, “Many of the Southern and Northern leaders, including Christian political leaders, are enmeshed in massive corruption, which makes them afraid to speak-out, because they fear a dusting up of their corruption files.” “I believes that “2023 will usher-in completely new leadership in Nigeria, it will be an opportunity for new-generation leaders with zero corruption baggage, and 21st Century credentials to emerge on the political stage,” he added.  